# Go 1.22 Cursor Rules

## Project Structure
- Follow Standard Go Project Layout: `cmd/`, `internal/`, `pkg/`
- `cmd/` — Main applications entry points
- `internal/` — Private application code (cannot be imported by other modules)
- `pkg/` — Public library code (importable by external projects)

## Error Handling
- Always check and handle errors — never use `_` to ignore errors
- Return errors as the last return value
- Use `fmt.Errorf("context: %w", err)` for error wrapping
- Use custom error types for domain errors
- Use `errors.Is()` and `errors.As()` for error checking
- DON'T: Use `panic()` for business logic errors — only for truly unrecoverable situations

## Concurrency
- Use goroutines for concurrent work, channels for communication
- Use `context.Context` for cancellation and timeouts
- Use `sync.WaitGroup` for waiting on multiple goroutines
- Use `sync.Mutex` for shared state (prefer channels when possible)
- Always handle goroutine cleanup — avoid goroutine leaks
- Use `errgroup` for concurrent operations with error handling

## Code Style
- Use `gofmt` / `goimports` for formatting (non-negotiable)
- Use meaningful variable names (not single letters except loop vars)
- Exported names are PascalCase, unexported are camelCase
- Interfaces are named with `-er` suffix: `Reader`, `Writer`, `Closer`
- Keep functions short and focused — one responsibility

## Performance
- Use `sync.Pool` for frequently allocated objects
- Profile with `pprof` before optimizing
- Use `strings.Builder` for string concatenation
- Avoid allocations in hot paths
- Use buffered channels for producer-consumer patterns
